ğŸŒ What is VirusTotal?
VirusTotal is a free online cybersecurity service that analyzes suspicious files, URLs, IP addresses, and domains to detect malware, viruses, and other threats using over 70 antivirus engines and threat intelligence feeds. It was originally created by Spanish security company Hispasec Sistemas in 2004 and was acquired by Google in September 2012.â€‹

ğŸ” How it works
VirusTotal operates on a multiscanning principleâ€”when you upload a file or submit a URL/IP address, it aggregates results from dozens of antivirus products and online scan engines (called "Contributors"). The platform scans your submission against all these engines simultaneously and provides a comprehensive detection report showing how many vendors flagged it as malicious.â€‹

ğŸ¯ What you can scan
ğŸ“ Files (up to 650 MB): executables, documents, APKs, scripts, archivesâ€‹

ğŸ”— URLs: suspicious links, phishing sites, malicious websitesâ€‹

ğŸŒ IP addresses: check reputation and threat intelligenceâ€‹

ğŸ·ï¸ Domains: analyze domain reputation and relationshipsâ€‹

ğŸ” File hashes (SHA-256, MD5): check if a file has been scanned beforeâ€‹

ğŸ‘¥ Who uses it?
VirusTotal is used by security professionals, SOC analysts, malware researchers, IT administrators, penetration testers, and even everyday users who want to verify suspicious downloads or email attachments before opening them. It's particularly valuable for small teams without access to expensive threat intelligence platforms.â€‹

âš ï¸ Key limitations
Not an antivirus replacement: VirusTotal only scans and reportsâ€”it doesn't remove malware from your deviceâ€‹

Public data: Uploaded files are shared with security partners, so avoid uploading sensitive documentsâ€‹

False positives possible: If only 1-2 engines detect something while 70+ mark it clean, it might be a false positiveâ€‹

